Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}.

When boiling, add the @penne pasta{180%g} to the water and bring back to the
boil. Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back into the pan. Drizzle with
@oil{1%drizzle} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{1%drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken thigh{260%g} and season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken
and its packaging.

Fry until golden brown on the outside, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the garlic and @Cajun spice mix{1} (add less if you'd prefer things milder)
to the pan. Cook, stirring frequently, for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @tomato passata{1}, @chicken stock paste{10%g} and @water{100%ml}
for the sauce (see pantry for amount).

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat. Simmer, stirring occasionally, until
thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Once the sauce has thickened, stir through half the @grated hard Italian style
cheese{10%g}, followed by the @creme fraiche{75%g}.

Bring to the boil, stirring, then remove from the heat. IMPORTANT: The chicken
is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Add the cooked pasta to the creamy sauce and mix well to combine. Reheat until
piping hot if needed.

Share the creamy Cajun chicken pasta between your #bowls{}.

Sprinkle over the remaining @grated hard Italian style cheese{10%g} to finish.
Enjoy!